ith-it\">Terence Stamp: ‘I was in my prime, but when the 60s ended, I ended with it’</a> </p> </aside>  <p>The movie is famous for Troy’s phallic swordplay as he teasingly slices and dices the very air around the dazzled Bathsheba. Viewed now, the scene looks creepier and pornier than ever, and the itinerant Troy almost seems like a serial killer. The painterly close-up gallery of rustic faces in this movie is tremendous – particularly that of Freddie Jones (father of Toby), playing Cainy Ball – and the singing scenes at harvest supper are wonderful. Finch and Stamp , in their differing ways, show the emotional masochism and self-destruction in Hardy’s male characters, and the candour and charm of Bates’s initial “proposal” scene are superbly done. Christie carries the film with her own insouciant vulnerability. A classic.</p>","headline":"Far from the Madding Crowd review – seductive swordplay, psychedelic cows","trailText":"Julie Christie is luminous and Terence Stamp a blade-twirling dazzler in John Schlesinger’s classic adaptation of Thomas Hardy","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/3/11/1426096265881/Psychedelic-masterpiece---001.jpg","wordcount":"243","commentable":"true","starRating":"5","byline":"Peter Bradshaw","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2015-03-15T22:00:04Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/mar/12/far-from-the-madding-crowd-1967-review-julie-christie-terence-stamp","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/film/2015/mar/12/far-from-the-madding-crowd-1967-review-julie-christie-terence-stamp","sectionName":"Film","tags":[{"id":"film/far-from-the-madding-crowd","webTitle":"Far From the Madding Crowd","type":"keyword","sectionId":"film","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/film/far-from-the-madding-crowd","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/film/far-from-the-madding-crowd","sectionName":"Film","references":[]},{"id":"film/film","webTitle":"Film","type":"keyw