http://gu.com/p/46t7b","standfirst":"Film director and writer whose own illness informed the making of Still Alice, the award-winning movie about Alzheimer’s","hasStoryPackage":"false","body":"<p>Richard Glatzer, who has died aged 63 from the progressive neurodegenerative disease ALS, was the co-writer and co-director, with his husband, Wash Westmoreland, of the award-winning film <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/still-alice\" title=\"\">Still Alice</a> (2014). It was the fourth directing collaboration for the couple, who met in 1995 and married in 2013. Asked in 2006 about the overlap between their personal and professional lives, Glatzer said: “We decided that if we were going to direct together, the best move would be to sleep together.”</p> <p>They adapted Still Alice from the self-published 2007 novel of the same name by the neuroscientist Lisa Genova. The film, about the gradual mental decline of a linguistics professor who is diagnosed in her 50s with early-onset Alzheimer’s disease, was given an extra emotional charge by Glatzer’s steadily worsening condition. He began to exhibit symptoms shortly before the couple decided to adapt Genova’s novel, with the official diagnosis coming in 2013. Julianne Moore, who won the best actress prize from all the major awards bodies for her performance in the lead role, reflected on this in her Oscar acceptance speech: “When Richard was diagnosed with ALS, Wash asked him what he wanted to do. Did he want to travel? Did he want to see the world? And he said that he wanted to make movies, and that’s what he did.”</p> <p>Still Alice spared audiences much of the physical deterioration associated with degenerative illness, concentrating instead on the confusion, anger and sadness experienced by its main character and her family, including her husband (Alec Baldwin) and their three adult children. The picture’s greatest strength is its ability to evoke the sort of subtle slippages in time and memory that become commonplace to Alzheimer’s sufferers. Discovering in the kitchen the phone that we saw her searching for in the previous scene, Alice exclaims: “I was looking for that last night!” Her husband turns to his daughter and whispers: “That was a month ago.” The disorientation we experience is all the greater for being muffled.</p> <p>“When we were adapting the book, a lot of personal stuff went in there from Richard,” said Westmoreland. “I think a lot of his feeling about his own situation percolated through into Alice. Even when he was on set he was directing with one finger using a voice app on an iPad. It sort of inspired the cast and crew. This is what we’re making the movie about: diseases can come but the people are still there.”</p> <p>Glatzer was born in Flushing, New York. He was raised in Long Island, New York, and in Livingston, New Jersey, and graduated from the University of Michigan. He also earned a doctorate in English from the University of Virginia, where he ran the film department and struck up an important friendship with Frank Capra. The general upswing in interest in Capra’s work during the 1970s has been credited to Glatzer.</p> <p>He moved to Los Angeles in the 1980s and worked with the screenwriter <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/news/2006/may/05/guardianobituaries.obituaries1\" title=\"\">Jay Presson Allen</a> (Marnie, Cabaret) and her producer husband <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/news/2000/may/13/guardianobituaries\" title=\"\">Lewis Allen</a>, whom he counted as mentors. Glatzer began his career in reality television with the daytime show Divorce Court. His experiences there partly inspired his first feature, Grief (1993), which portrayed the off-screen exploits of the cast and crew of a tacky soap called The Love Judge. While the camp humour suggested that Glatzer was following in John Waters’s footsteps (one of the plot-lines concerns the provenance of an unsightly stain on the office sofa), there was poignancy too: the title refers to the death from Aids of the main character’s partner.</p> <p>He continued to work in television – his CV was peppered with hit shows such as The Osbournes and America’s Next Top Model – and also ran the underground Los Angeles club Sit-and-Spin. He later returned to film in collaboration with Westmoreland. They co-directed <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/90937/fluffer\" title=\"\">The Fluffer</a> (2001), a low-budget comedy about the adult film industry; the title refers to the crew member whose job it is to keep the leading man on a porn shoot fit for purpose. Westmoreland wrote the screenplay, which was informed by his own background directing porn movies.</p> <p>The couple teamed up next to co-write and co-direct <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/echo-park-la\" title=\"\">Quinceañera</a> (2006), set in the Echo Park area of Los Angeles, where they were living at the time. The script examined both Latino culture in the US and the gentrification that was creeping into Mexican neighbourhoods. Production was fast – the picture was written, cast and shot in under three months – and the budget low. “We approached it as if it was a documentary,” said Glazter, who also cited the British kitchen-sink drama A Taste of Honey as a major influence on Quinceañera. The film, which won the audience award and the grand jury prize at the Sundance film festival, presented a fond portrait of the Latino community but also featured a self-critique in the form of two gay characters loosely based by the film-makers on themselves.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"16942add44ff963582ce69a108ac2269281ada90\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/3/12/1426186244142/615dfee7-d4c0-47dd-a848-e6875fcb167e-460x276.jpeg\" alt=\"Julianne Moore in Still Alice, co-written and co-directed by Richard Glatzer and Wash Westmoreland. Moore won the best actress prize from all the major awards bodies for her performance.\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Julianne Moore in Still Alice, co-written and co-directed by Richard Glatzer and Wash Westmoreland. Moore won the best actress prize from all the major awards bodies for her performance.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Artificial Eye/Allstar</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>“We thought as gay men we have the freedom to be more critical of the gay community than people outside it,” he said. “I’ve heard those conversations. Everybody buys houses and sees the property value go up and people think that’s great but we also thought it would be great to draw the gay community’s attention to the fact that something is being lost and also, if you want to fuck somebody and don’t want to invite them to dinner – that’s kind of cruel. We want to draw attention a little bit to the coded racism where you fetishise something different but because it’s different you don’t want to go beyond the physical.”</p> <p>Glatzer and Westmoreland were among the producers of Pedro (2008), a film about the gay Cuban-American reality TV star Pedro Zamora. They also co-wrote and co-directed <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2013/jan/24/kevin-kline-errol-flynn-sex-scandal\" title=\"\">The Last of Robin Hood </a>(2013) starring Kevin Kline as Errol Flynn. The movie documented the relationship between the ageing actor and a 17-year-old chorus girl. It met with a mixed reception, much like all their films. Until Still Alice, that is, which was acclaimed almost universally.</p> <p>Glatzer is survived by Westmoreland.</p> <p>• Richard Glatzer, writer and director, born 28 January 1952; died 10 March 2015</p>","headline":"Richard Glatzer obituary","trailText":"Film director and writer whose own illness informed the making of Still Alice, the award-winning movie about Alzheimer’s","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/3/12/1426184866231/Richard-Glatzer-001.jpg","wordcount":"1060","commentable":"true","byline":"Ryan Gilbey","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2015-03-26T18:29:00+00:00"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/mar/12/richard-glatzer","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/film/2015/mar/12/richard-glatzer","sectionName":"Film","tags":[{"id":"film/still-alice","webTitle":"Still Alice","type":"keyword","sectionId":"film","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/film/still-alice","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/film/still-alice","sectionName":"Film","references":[]},{"id":"tone/obituaries","webTitle":"Obituaries","type":"tone","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/tone/obituaries","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/tone/obituaries","references":[]},{"id":"film/film","webTitle":"Film","type":"keyword","sectionId":"film","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/film/film","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/film/film","sectionName":"Film","references":[]},{"id":"culture/culture","webTitle":"Culture","type":"keyword","sectionId":"culture","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/culture/culture","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/culture/culture","sectionName":"Culture","references":[]},{"id":"film/film-adaptations","webTitle":"Film adaptations","type":"keyword","sectionId":"film","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/film/film-adaptations","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/film/film-adaptations","sectionName":"Film","references":[]},{"id":"books/books","webTitle":"Books","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/books","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/books","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"film/oscars","webTitle":"Oscars","type":"keyword","sectionId":"film","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/film/oscars","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/film/oscars","sectionName":"Film","references":[]},{"id":"culture/awards-and-prizes","webTitle":"Awards