ut air travel, and looked back in fondness at our Founding Fathers who refused to pay their taxes. One thing was different, though: we didn&apos;t go to the movies. This holiday weekend took a 44% dip in American ticket sales from 2013. If you adjust for inflation it was the worst 4 July weekend since 1987.</p> <p>The capability to stream TV and movies (legally and otherwise) is reminding studios that their product needs to be enticing enough to warrant the time and expense of a theater visit. Last weekend&apos;s openers Tammy and Deliver Us From Evil were pretty much reviled by most critics. With the summer halfway done, is there anything good on the horizon?</p> <p>Unfortunately, the answer is: not much. It isn&apos;t all bleak, but compared to the summers of our youth (and it isn&apos;t just nostalgia: the 80s and 90s really knew how to pack a season of blockbusters) it&apos;s a desert out there. Below are the very few oases for filmgoers between now and Labor Day, with US release dates listed.</p> <h2>Big movies that will be good</h2> <p><b><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/dawn-of-the-planet-of-the-apes-film\">Dawn of the Planet of the Apes</a> (11 July)</b><br /></p> <p>“Who asked for this?” I snarked as I entered the theater during 2011&apos;s Rise of the Planet of the Apes. “Buck, I will avenge thee!” I wept as the film ended. Rise began a little hokey, and no one is going to accuse Freida Pinto of giving a good performance, but take state-of-the-art motion capturing, ambiguous moral culpability, a few bananas and you have a thrilling action film. The sequel, Dawn, takes place after society&apos;s downfall as Caesar (once again a computer-enhanced Andy Serkis) leads his simian armies through war and peace. The film, like some of the original Apes movies, mixes intellect and allegory with adventure and special effects. A number of critics have already applauded Matt Reeves, best known for directing Cloverfield, for delivering an Empire Strikes Back-level entertainment for this new trilogy. (Yep: the third instalment has already been greenlit.)</p> <p><b><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/155488/guardians-of-the-galaxy\">Guardians of the Galaxy</a> (1 August)</b></p>  <figure class=\"element element-video\" data-canonical-url=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2LIQ2-PZBC8\"                                                                                                > <iframe width=\"460\" height=\"259\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/2LIQ2-PZBC8?wmode=opaque&feature=oembed\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe> <figcaption> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>This is Marvel Studio head Kevin Feige&apos;s victory lap. When The Avengers became the third highest grossing picture ever, the bean counters at Disney shrugged and said, sure, take something from comic book lore out for a spin. Thus we get director James Gunn, whose last film was the anti-superhero picture Super, tackling the weirdest collection of deep cut oddities in Marvel canon. Guardians of the Galaxy features Bradley Cooper as a gun-toting, talking raccoon, and Vin Diesel as a sentient tree creature from Planet X. This more resembles the 80s space adventure The Ice Pirates than Captain America. Chris Pratt as the rogueish leader and Zoe Saldana (green this time, not blue) zip around in cool ships saving the day, zinging each other with jokes. I must confess, I&apos;ve been keeping my head in the sand on this one, trying to avoid too much specific info. I love nerdy superhero sci-fi, and once I saw the soundtrack was wall-to-wall 70s pop (10cc! Jackson 5! The Raspberries!) I cut myself off from watching any clips. A critic can still be a fan.</p> <h2>Big movies that will be dumb but maybe fun (Maybe)</h2> <p><b><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hercules_(2014_film)\">Hercules</a> (25 July)</b></p> <p>This movie will be bad. Director Brett Ratner is basically the poor man&apos;s Michael Bay. But Dwayne Johnson is a charisma machine. If I said to you I didn&apos;t want to see him shirtlessly accomplishing his heroic twelve labors I&apos;d be a liar. Plus, this movie co-stars Ian McShane, who is either Al Swearengin or Emperor Palpatine. I get the two confused, but they&apos;re both great, so whichever it is, we win.</p> <p><b><a href=\"http://www.imdb.com/title/tt2872732/\">Lucy</a> (25 July)</b></p>  <figure class=\"element element-video\" data-canonical-url=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MVt32qoyhi0\"                                                                                                > <iframe width=\"460\" height=\"259\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/MVt32qoyhi0?wmode=opaque&feature=oembed\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe> <figcaption> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>My anticipation of Lucy is much the same as Hercules. Director Luc Besson&apos;s name on a project has lately become the kiss of death for actual quality, but he does tend to deliver a certain kind of good time. Lucy features Scarlett Johansson running around Taipei making time stop and people fly across the room, and she probably wears sexy wigs and says quotable things in that deep voice of hers, before shots of a gorgeous stunt double spins around like a human top. Listen: I live in New York City and by 25 July it is so disgustingly hot that the air conditioning of a movie theater is a very real necessity. Watching ScoJo beat the crap out of baddies is more than adequate accompaniment for a good session of climate control.<br /></p> <p><b><a href=\"http://www.imdb.com/title/tt1924435/\">Let&apos;s Be Cops</a> (13 August)</b></p> <p>Damon Wayans and Jake Johnson play two dinguses who dress like cops for a costume party and discover that people treat them with respect. So they continue to pretend to be cops. Shenanigans ensue. Any premise this simple is just a little bit genius. I confess to laughing at the trailer.</p> <h2>Small movies that will be great</h2> <p>Listen up, you rubes. You don&apos;t have to just see what the rich monsters in Hollywood force-feed you through the studio system. What about the rich monsters producing lower-budget films? Keep your eyes peeled for these titles coming out during the second part of the summer. </p> <p><b><a href=\"http://www.imdb.com/title/tt1065073/\">Boyhood</a> (11 July)</b></p>  <figure class=\"element element-video\" data-canonical-url=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/video/2014/jul/08/boyhood-richard-linklater-ellar-coltrane-interview-video\"                                        data-show-ads=\"true\"                data-video-id=\"2121591\"                data-video-name=\"Richard Linklater and Ellar Coltrane on Boyhood: 'You're collaborating with an unknown future' – video interviews\"                data-video-provider=\"guardian.co.uk\"                data-video-poster=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/audio/video/2014/7/4/1404486226273/Boyhood-010.jpg\"> <video data-media-id=\"gu-video-441294572\" class=\"gu-video\" controls=\"controls\" poster=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/audio/video/2014/7/4/1404486222754/Boyhood-008.jpg\"> <source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/mainwebsite/2014/07/04/140704Boyhood-16x9.mp4\"></source><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/HLS/2014/07/04/140704Boyhood/140704Boyhood.m3u8\"></source><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/3gp/large/2014/07/04/140704Boyhood_3gpLg16x9.3gp\"></source><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/3gp/small/2014/07/04/140704Boyhood_3gpSml16x9.3gp\"></source><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/webM/2014/07/04/140704Boyhood.webm\"></source> </video> </figure>  <p>Something of a minor miracle. Director Richard Linklater shot this movie in small doses over 12 years, slowly chronicling a young boy&apos;s maturation. It&apos;s a big movie made up of small moments, genuinely touching and wholly unpredictable. Get on the bandwagon now, as every critic worth his or her salt will list it on their end-of-year top 10.</p> <p><b><a href=\"http://www.imdb.com/title/tt2027140/?ref_=nv_sr_1\">Mood Indigo</a> (18 July)<br /></b></p> <p>Arguably the most French movie ever made, Romain Duris and Audrey Tautou are quite adorable as fairy tale lovers in Michel Gondry&apos;s adaptation of Boris Vian&apos;s Froth on the Daydream. This highly energetic picture isn&apos;t for everyone – but if you like your whimsical magical realism done up in an antic, extra-crafty style, this may just win your heart.</p> <p><b><a href=\"http://www.imdb.com/title/tt2870756/?ref_=nv_sr_1\">Magic in the Moonlight</a> (25 July)</b></p>  <figure class=\"element element-video\" data-canonical-url=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LAwbwKURvm0\"                                                                                                > <iframe width=\"460\" height=\"259\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/LAwbwKURvm0?wmode=opaque&feature=oembed\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe> <figcaption> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>The latest from Woody Allen is something of a small gem, with Colin Firth and Emma Stone sauntering through a 1930s-era Côte d&apos;Azur, saying witty things about magic and love and faith. Many of Allen&apos;s films have been set in an earlier era, few actually feel this much like an actual relic. In this case, it is meant as a high compliment.<br /></p> <p><b><a href=\"http://www.imdb.com/title/tt2234003/?ref_=nv_sr_1\">Calvary</a> (1 August)</b></p> <p>Writer-director John Michael McDonough and actor Brendan Gleeson re-team for this funny yet melancholy look at the proverbial “good Irish priest” and a small village of idiosyncratic characters – one of which has pledged to murder Gleeson in a week&apos;s time. Chris O&apos;Down, Domhnall Gleeson, Isaach de Bankolé and Aidan Gillen co-star.</p> <p><b><a href=\"http://www.imdb.com/title/tt2194328/?ref_=fn_al_tt_1\">Finding Fela!</a> (1 August)</b></p> <p>Director Alex Gibney pumps out documentaries like Wendy&apos;s chicken sandwiches, but there&apos;s no possible way to screw this up. Even if the talking heads are a snooze, any archival footage of Fela Kuti performing will make this a must-see.</p> <p><b><a href=\"http://www.imdb.com/title/tt1605717/?ref_=nv_sr_1\">Frank</a> (15 August)</b></p>  <figure class=\"element element-video\" data-canonical-url=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/video/2014/may/07/frank-domhnall-gleeson-jon-ronson-video-interview\"                                        data-show-ads=\"true\"                data-video-id=\"2088400\"                data-video-name=\"Frank star Domhnall Gleeson and co-writer Jon Ronson: 'We're not very forgiving of transgressions any more' – video interview\"                data-video-provider=\"guardian.co.uk\"                data-video-poster=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/audio/video/2014/5/7/1399468086126/Frank-star-Domhnall-Glees-014.jpg\"> <video data-media-id=\"gu-video-436250522\" class=\"gu-video\" controls=\"controls\" poster=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/audio/video/2014/5/7/1399468084591/Frank-star-Domhnall-Glees-013.jpg\"> <source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/mainwebsite/2014/05/07/140507Frank-16x9.mp4\"></source><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/3gp/small/2014/05/07/140507Frank_3gpSml16x9.3gp\"></source><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/3gp/large/2014/05/07/140507Frank_3gpLg16x9.3gp\"></source><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/webM/2014/05/07//140507Frank.webm\"></source><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/HLS/2014/05/07/140507Frank/140507Frank.m3u8\"></source> </video> </figure>  <p>Loosely based on essayist Jon Ronson&apos;s youthful exploits as a keyboard player for Frank Sidebottom&apos;s band, this surreal rock comedy featuring Michael Fassbender in an enormous papier mâché head is a touching and sincere look at mental illness and the dangers of perceived genius. The last five minutes make for quite possibly the best finish in any film this year.</p> <p><b><a href=\"http://www.imdb.com/title/tt2581244/?ref_=nv_sr_1\">Life After Beth</a> (15 August)</b></p> <p>Aubrey Plaza deserves to be a bigger star, and maybe this horror-comedy is the one that will make it happen. Dane DeHaan, John C Reilly, Molly Shannon and a lot of other people you recognize co-star in this story of a wiseacre girl who becomes a zombie. (Now&apos;s when you reread the title and realize its genius.)</p> <p><b><a href=\"http://www.imdb.com/title/tt1821641/?ref_=fn_al_tt_1\">The Congress</a> (29 August)</b></p> <p>Israeli director Ari Folman&apos;s follow-up to the politically charged Waltz With Bashir is a strange mix of Hollywood satire and psychedelic sci-fi mind trip. It begins as a satire on advancements in cinematic technology, then morphs down an animated rabbit hole of delusion and addiction. It&apos;s also virtually impossible to sum up, but if you like far-out “head” films you&apos;ll miss this one at your peril.</p>","headline":"Summer film preview: what do we have to look forward to?","trailText":"With the summer halfway done, we take a look at upcoming releases from Michel Gondry to Dawn of the Planet of the Apes","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/7/8/1404828277205/756a353c-7883-4ab6-82f6-142f4a27736a-140x84.jpeg","wordcount":"1350","commentable":"true","byline":"Jordan Hoffman","productionOffice":"US","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-07-11T10:15:00-04:00"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/jul/08/us-summer-movies-preview-planet-of-apes","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/film/2014/jul/08/us-summer-movies-preview-planet-of-apes","sectionName":"Film","tags":[{"id":"film/film","webTitle":"Film","type":"keyword","sectionId":"film","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/film/film","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/film/film","sectionName":"Film","references":[]},{"id":"culture/culture","webTitle":"Culture","type":"keyword","sectionId":"culture","webU