andfirst":"Event's director hopes initiative will revive LA as a go-to location and result in a new clutch of classic movies","hasStoryPackage":"false","body":"<p>When Hollywood reigned supreme in the film industry, movie buffs were frequently able to spot characteristic landmarks of Los Angeles on the big screen.</p><p>From the distinctive boulevard palms in <em>Beverly Hills Cop</em> to the Green Harbour bridge for the bungee jump in <em>To Live and Die in LA</em> and the compelling backdrop for <em>Chinatown</em>, the city made its mark on the movies. Now, with the industry shrinking and studios moving to countries with bigger subsidies and incentives for film-making, Hollywood's attention is returning home.</p><p>The Los Angeles film festival celebrates the city's movie culture with a new section devoted to movies made in and about LA. The local industry reached its peak in 1996, the year Tom Cruise starred in <em>Jerry Maguire</em>, when the number of feature film location shooting days reached a total of 13,980. That number fell to 4,976 in 2009 and, with the help of a small state subsidy, rose slightly to 6,972 days last year.</p><p>Stephanie Allain, the festival's director, said she thought a renewed emphasis on Los Angeles was appropriate. \"There's still a lot of energy here. People come here to realise their dreams.\"</p><p>Yet LA barely figured in the most prominent movies of 2013 with only one of the nine nominees for the year's best picture Oscar, <em>Her</em>, set in the city.</p><p>Allain said the new section of the festival, running from June 11-19, will be called LA Muse. The schedule for the festival is still being finalised but she said it would include about 10 specially designated Los Angeles moments, including the world premiere of a small film, <a href=\"http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0090994/\" title=\"\"><em>Echo Park</em></a><em>,</em> which was shot mostly in the neighbourhood of that name, where young bohemians and professionals bump up against the Latin side of the city's life.</p><p>She said her favourite LA film was <em>Chinatown</em> and that her own latest work was also set in the city. The film <em>Blackbird</em>, a story about musical stardom, written and directed by <a href=\"http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0697656/\" title=\"\">Gina Prince-Bythewood</a>, is to be released in November by Relativity Media.</p><p>\"We did budget for incentive states but at the end of the day, it's an LA story,\" Allain said of the decision to film locally. She believes that the industry is due for a revival, despite the financial incentives to shoot in other states or, more likely, other countries. \"People dream stuff up here,\" she said.</p><p>There is also a new push to give cash incentives to film-makers. Hollywood's unions have been pressing Californian officials to help promote film production by expanding state subsidies and there is soon to be a vote on a proposal. However, Kenneth Ziffren, the director of the City of Los Angeles's Entertainment Industry and Production Office, said last week that its prospects remain uncertain.</p><p>Now in her third year as director, Allain is also planning to publish an annual poster designed by a changing roster of Los Angeles artists. This year's entry, by <a href=\"http://www.edruscha.com/\" title=\"\">Edward Ruscha</a>, offers a looming logo featuring spotlights that seems to mimic the classic trademark of 20th Century Fox.</p>","headline":"Festival aims to put Hollywood back in the frame with bid to recapture the glory days","trailText":"Event's director hopes initiative will revive LA as a go-to location and result in a new clutch of classic movies, writes <strong>Lin Jenkins</strong>","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Travel/Late_offers/pictures/2014/3/8/1394317658248/Chinatown-006.jpg","wordcount":"494","commentable":"true","byline":"Lin Jenkins","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-03-15T22:34:00Z"},"webUrl":"htt