c.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/8/14/1376473375923/London-After-Midnight-007.jpg","typeData":{"displayCredit":"true","source":"University of Chicago Press","altText":"Silent Film Photography: London After Midnight","height":"509","credit":"University of Chicago Press","caption":"<strong>London after Midnight, 1927</strong><br/> The holy grail for many a silent film collector, Tod Browning's London After Midnight is a lost film – the last remaining copy is thought to have been burned in a fire at the MGM vault in 1967. Stills such as this one, by Bert Longworth, reveal why it is so highly sought after. Lon Chaney and Edna Tichenor play the ghoulish and mysterious strangers who appear in a dead man's house five years after his apparent suicide. It is characteristic of Longworth's stills work that the figures, while central to the composition, are dominated by the architecture – also that the camera is positioned at a low angle and the shadows are distorted. Longworth was fascinated by the expressionist films made in Germany, and it shows","width":"400"}},{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/8/14/1376473375923/London-After-Midnight-007-thumb-3932.jpg","typeData":{"displayCredit":"true","source":"University of Chicago Press","altText":"Silent Film Photography: London After Midnight","height":"68","credit":"University of Chicago Press","caption":" Wallace Chewning: Lon Chaney Sr. and Edna Tichenor as Prof. Edward C. Burke and Luna the Bat Girl in London after Midnight, Hollywood, Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer, December 17, 1927\r","width":"68"}}]},{"id":"gu-image-414995750","relation":"gallery","type":"image","galleryIndex":3,"assets":[{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/8/14/1376473363897/Clara-Bow-002.jpg","typeData":{"displayCredit":"true","source":"University of Chicago Press","altText":"Silent Film Photography: Clara Bow","height":"518","credit":"University of Chicago Press","caption":"<strong>Clara Bow, 1923</strong><br/> This portrait of Clara Bow by Max Munn Autrey is as chilling as it is glamorous – capturing the star's beauty but also an unnervingly blank expression. Bow's fashionable heavy makeup and outrageously bouncy bobbed hair are highlighted by soft 'beauty' lighting, but undermined by that jumper. This photograph was taken in 1923, the year that Bow left her impoverished home in a tenement in Prospect Heights, New York, to move to Hollywood. She would become one of the silent era's biggest stars, but this image catches her in transition between Brooklyn and LA","width":"400"}},{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/8/14/1376473363897/Clara-Bow-002-thumb-6481.jpg","typeData":{"displayCredit":"true","source":"University of Chicago Press","altText":"Silent Film Photography: Clara Bow","height":"68","credit":"University of Chicago Press","caption":"Clara Bow, 1923","width":"68"}}]},{"id":"gu-image-414995752","relation":"gallery","type":"image","galleryIndex":4,"assets":[{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/8/14/1376473368902/Flames-004.jpg","typeData":{"displayCredit":"true","source":"University of Chicago Press","altText":"Silent Film Photography: Flames","height":"480","credit":"University of Chicago Press","caption":"<strong>Fighting the Flames, Dreamland, 1904</strong><br/>The Dreamland amusement park in Coney Island opened in 1904, and was razed in a massive fire in 1911. Strange, then, that its biggest attraction in the early days was <a href=\"http://www.astropop.com/coney/pages/4a17578a.htm\">Fighting the Flames</a>, a spectacle in which firefighters paraded on their horse-drawn engines before extinguishing a simulated fire at a multi-storey hotel, and rescuing the distraught 'guests'. This is a specially taken promotional image for Fighting the Flames, Dreamland, an actuality film photographed in the park's first year of business by one Billy Bitzer for the Biograph company in New York. Both Bitzer and Biograph are best known now for their associations with the director DW Griffith; Bitzer was his favoured cinematographer, Biograph the studio where he made his first films, beginning with The Adventures of Dollie in 1908","width":"599"}},{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/8/14/1376473368902/Flames-004-thumb-1436.jpg","typeData":{"displayCredit":"true","source":"University of Chicago Press","altText":"Silent Film Photography: Flames","height":"68","credit":"University of Chicago Press","caption":" [Billy Bitzer]: Fighting the Flames, Dreamland, 1904, \r","width":"68"}}]},{"id":"gu-image-414995785","relation":"gallery","type":"image","galleryIndex":5,"assets":[{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/8/14/1376473366384/Marie-Prevost-003.jpg","typeData":{"displayCredit":"true","source":"University of Chicago Press","altText":"Silent Film Photography: Marie Prevost","height":"514","credit":"University of Chicago Press","caption":"<strong>Marie Prevost, 1917</strong><br/>A fine, perhaps underrated, comic actor, Marie Prevost is pictured here by Nelson Evans in her early days as one of Mack Sennett's Bathing Beauties. Evans is credited with inventing the classic Hollywood 'cheescake' style, thanks to flirty shots such as this one. He was also renowned for retouching his frames, often engraving his glass negative plates. The surf around Prevost's ankles here may well have been manipulated. Sadly, Prevost's career began to decline in the late 1920s and a combination of binge eating and alcoholism would go on to destroy her looks and mental health. The booze eventually killed her in 1937","width":"400"}},{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/