, Kay-Bee Pictures, March 5, 1916\r","width":"68"}}]},{"id":"gu-image-414995746","relation":"gallery","type":"image","galleryIndex":7,"assets":[{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/8/14/1376473373614/Caligari-006.jpg","typeData":{"displayCredit":"true","source":"University of Chicago Press","altText":"Silent Film Photography: Caligari","height":"480","credit":"University of Chicago Press","caption":"<strong>The Cabinet of Dr Caligari, 1920</strong><br/>Lil Dagover cowers on possibly the most recognisable set in film history – the nightmare landscape of Robert Wiene's <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/77300/cabinet-of-dr-caligari\">The Cabinet of Dr Caligari</a>. Hermann Warm's boldly expressionist designs for the film, with their tipsy angles and long shadows, encapsulate its twisting plot and air of paranoia. Cinematographer Willy Hameister's camera tilts downwards, an unsettling angle that further exaggerates the effect","width":"650"}},{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/8/14/1376473373614/Caligari-006-thumb-2073.jpg","typeData":{"displayCredit":"true","source":"University of Chicago Press","altText":"Silent Film Photography: Caligari","height":"68","credit":"University of Chicago Press","caption":"[Willy Hameister]: Lil Dagover as Jane in The Cabinet of Dr. Caligari, Berlin, Decia-Bioscop AG, American release March 19, 1921","width":"68"}}]},{"id":"gu-image-414995766","relation":"gallery","type":"image","galleryIndex":8,"assets":[{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/8/14/1376473371343/Francis-X-Bushman-005.jpg","typeData":{"displayCredit":"true","source":"University of Chicago Press","altText":"Silent Film Photography: Francis X Bushman","height":"505","credit":"University of Chicago Press","caption":"<strong>The Grip of the Yukon, 1928 </strong><br/>Bodybuilder turned actor Francis X Bushman (the X stands for Xavier) was dubbed \"The Handsomest Man in the World\" by studio publicity and made nearly 200 films, mostly in the 1910s, very few of which survive today. He is most familiar now for his performance as Messala in the 1925 Ben Hur. This striking still from lost film The Grip of the Yukon was taken by Jack Freulich. It's typical of Freulich's film star portraits in that it emphasises character over physical perfection – here the man they nicknamed Francis \"Sex\" Bushman is a haunted soul rather than a hunk","width":"400"}},{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/8/14/1376473371343/Francis-X-Bushman-005-thumb-6310.jpg","typeData":{"displayCredit":"true","source":"University of Chicago Press","altText":"Silent Film Photography: Francis X Bushman","height":"68","credit":"University of Chicago Press","caption":" Jack Freulich: Francis X. Bushman as Colby MacDonald in The Grip of the Yukon,\rHollywood, Universal Pictures, July 9, 1928","width":"68"}}]},{"id":"gu-image-414995744","relation":"gallery","type":"image","galleryIndex":9,"assets":[{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/8/14/1376473383200/Beaucaire-010.jpg","typeData":{"displayCredit":"true","source":"University of Chicago Press","altText":"Silent Film Photography: Beaucaire","height":"480","credit":"University of Chicago Press","caption":"<strong>Monsieur Beaucaire, 1924</strong><br/> Lois Wilson is the Queen of France, circled by attendants and accompanied by her lapdog in this typically lavish still from Paramount's Monsieur Beaucaire. Not pictured here is the film's star Rudolph Valentino, whose wife Natacha Rambova designed those fabulous costumes (at a cost of $215,000) as well as the sets. The film failed to recoup its generous budget at the box office and inevitably Rambova was criticised for her expensive interventions. Nevertheless, it's a gorgeous-looking film with first-rate cinematography by Harry Fischbeck. This publicity still by Russell Ball showcases Rambova's art direction and Fischbeck's lighting with an elegant and witty composition","width":"599"}},{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/8/14/1376473383200/Beaucaire-010-thumb-6397.jpg","typeData":{"displayCredit":"true","source":"University of Chicago Press","altText":"Silent Film Photography: Beaucaire","height":"68","credit":"University of Chicago Press","caption":"Russell Ball: Lois Wilson and cast as Queen Marie of France and attendants in Monsieur Beaucaire, New York, Paramount Pictures, August 11, 1924\r","width":"68"}}]},{"id":"gu-image-414995817","relation":"gallery","type":"image","galleryIndex":10,"assets":[{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/8/14/1376473361492/Nazimova-001.jpg","typeData":{"displayCredit":"true","source":"University of Chicago Press","altText":"Silent Film Photography: Nazimova","height":"490","credit":"University of Chicago Press","caption":"<strong>Salomé, 1923</strong><br/>Alla Nazimova, often known simply by her last name, was a writer, producer and actor and one of the most fascinating figures in silent film history. Salomé, an adaptation of the Oscar Wilde play, has become a cult classic, noted for Nazimova's dance of the seven veils and Natacha Rambova's Aubrey Beardsley-inspired designs. Crimea-born Nazimova was a lesbian, and while the rumour swirls that she and Natacha Rambova were lovers, it has never been confirmed. Far more outlandish, and even less likely to be true, is the story that Salomé was produced by an all-gay cast and crew. This eerie, sexy still by Arthur F Rice, the photographer that Shields labels a 'genius', captures the film, and its star, in all their decadent glory. 'In Rice's stills,' writes Shields, 'we see the subtlety of lighting and visual arrangement and read the dynamic of emotional conflict without caption.'","width":"400"}},{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/8/14/1376473361492/Nazimova-001-thumb-1244.jpg","typeData":{"displayCredit":"true","source":"University of Chicago Press","altText":"Silent Film Photography: Nazimova","height":"68","credit":"University of Chicago Press","caption":" Alla Nazimova, 1923, in Salome, Nazimova Productions, released February 13, 1923. Natacha Rambova, art direction\r","width":"68"}}]}]}]}}